14612   // previous store with the same distance.
14613   // Example:
14614   // 1. store x, %p
14615   // 2. store y, %p+1
14616   // 3. store z, %p+2
14617   // 4. store a, %p
14618   // 5. store b, %p+3
14619   // - Scan this from the last to first store. The very first bunch of stores is
14620   // {5, {{4, -3}, {2, -2}, {3, -1}, {5, 0}}} (the element in SortedStores
14621   // vector).
14622   // - The next store in the list - #1 - has the same distance from store #5 as
14623   // the store #4.
14624   // - Try to vectorize sequence of stores 4,2,3,5.
14625   // - If all these stores are vectorized - just drop them.
14626   // - If some of them are not vectorized (say, #3 and #5), do extra analysis.
14627   // - Start new stores sequence.
14628   // The new bunch of stores is {1, {1, 0}}.
14629   // - Add the stores from previous sequence, that were not vectorized.
14630   // Here we consider the stores in the reversed order, rather they are used in
